# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bump-charts
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] A **line chart** or **line graph**, also known as **curve chart**, is a type of chart that displays information as a series of data points called 'markers' connected by straight line segments.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] It is a basic type of chart common in many fields.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] It is similar to a scatter plot except that the measurement points are ordered (typically by their x-axis value) and joined with straight line segments.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] A line chart is often used to visualize a trend in data over intervals of time – a time series – thus the line is often drawn chronologically.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] In these cases they are known as run charts.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] Some of the earliest known line charts are generally credited to Francis Hauksbee, Nicolaus Samuel Cruquius, Johann Heinrich Lambert and the Scottish engineer William Playfair.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] Line charts often display time as a variable on the x-axis.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] Playfair was one of the first to visualize data this way.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] In 1786, he plotted ten years of money spent by the Royal Navy.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] He supplemented the chart with a detailed description, telling his readers how to interpret the change over time because they were unfamiliar with this form of abstract visualization.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] In addition to line charts, Playfair invented and popularized bar charts and pie charts.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] In the experimental sciences, data collected from experiments are often visualized by a graph.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] Such a table representation of data is a great way to display exact values, but it can prevent the discovery and understanding of patterns in the values.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] In addition, a table display is often erroneously considered to be an objective, neutral collection or storage of the data (and may in that sense even be erroneously considered to be the data itself) whereas it is in fact just one of various possible visualizations of the data.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] Understanding the process described by the data in the table is aided by producing a graph or line chart of *speed versus time*.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] Such a visualisation appears in the figure to the right.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] This visualization can let the viewer quickly understand the entire process at a glance.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] This visualization can however be misunderstood, especially when expressed as showing the mathematical function $v(t)$ that expresses the speed v (the dependent variable) as a function of time t .
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] This can be misunderstood as showing speed to be a variable that is dependent only on time.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] This would however only be true in the case of an object being acted on only by a constant force acting in a vacuum.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] Charts often include an overlaid mathematical function depicting the best-fit trend of the scattered data.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] This layer is referred to as a best-fit layer and the graph containing this layer is often referred to as a line graph.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] It is highly unlikely that the experimental error in the data is negligible, yet the curve falls exactly through each of the data points.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] In either case, the best-fit layer can reveal trends in the data.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] Further, measurements such as the gradient or the area under the curve can be made visually, leading to more conclusions or results from the data table.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] A true best-fit layer should depict a continuous mathematical function whose parameters are determined by using a suitable error-minimization scheme, which appropriately weights the error in the data values.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] Such curve fitting functionality is often found in graphing software or spreadsheets.
[src:bump-charts/line-chart] Best-fit curves may vary from simple linear equations to more complex quadratic, polynomial, exponential, and periodic curves.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] To plot, or visualize, a set of points in *n*-dimensional space, *n* parallel lines are drawn over the background representing coordinate axes, typically oriented vertically with equal spacing.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] Points in *n*-dimensional space are represented as individual polylines with *n* vertices placed on the parallel axes corresponding to each coordinate entry of the *n*-dimensional point, vertices are connected with *n-1* polyline segments.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] This data visualization is similar to time series visualization, except that Parallel Coordinates are applied to data which do not correspond with chronological time.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] Therefore, different axes arrangements can be of interest, including reflecting axes horizontally, otherwise inverting the attribute range.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] The concept of Parallel Coordinates is often said to originate in 1885 by a French mathematician Philbert Maurice d'Ocagne. d'Ocagne sought a way to provide graphical calculation of mathematical functions using alignment diagrams called nomograms which used parallel axes with different scales.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] For example, a three-variable equation could be solved using three parallel axes, marking known values on their scales, then drawing a line between them, with an unknown read from the scale at the point where the line intersects that scale.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] However, both d'Ocagne and Gannet were far preceded in this by André-Michel Guerry, Plate IV, "Influence de l'Age", where he showed rankings of crimes against persons by age along parallel axes, connecting the same crime across age groups.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] Parallel Coordinates were popularised again 87 years later by Alfred Inselberg in 1985 and systematically developed as a coordinate system starting from 1977.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] Some important applications are in collision avoidance algorithms for air traffic control (1987—3 USA patents), data mining (USA patent), computer vision (USA patent), Optimization, process control, more recently in intrusion detection and elsewhere.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] On the plane with an XY Cartesian coordinate system, adding more dimensions in parallel coordinates (often abbreviated ||-coords, PCP, or PC) involves adding more axes.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] The value of parallel coordinates is that certain geometrical properties in high dimensions transform into easily seen 2D patterns.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] For example, a set of points on a line in *n*-space transforms to a set of polylines in parallel coordinates all intersecting at *n* − 1 points.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] For *n* = 2 this yields a point-line duality pointing out why the mathematical foundations of parallel coordinates are developed in the projective rather than Euclidean space.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] A pair of lines intersects at a unique point which has two coordinates and, therefore, can correspond to a unique line which is also specified by two parameters (or two points).
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] In contrast, more than two points are required to specify a curve and also a pair of curves may not have a unique intersection.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] The goal is to map n-dimensional relations into 2D patterns.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] Hence, parallel coordinates is not a point-to-point mapping but rather a *n*D subset to 2D subset mapping, there is no loss of information.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] Note: even a point in nD is not mapped into a point in 2D, but to a polygonal line—a subset of 2D.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] When used for statistical data visualisation there are three important considerations: the order, the rotation, and the scaling of the axes.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] The order of the axes is critical for finding features, and in typical data analysis many reorderings will need to be tried.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] Some authors have come up with ordering heuristics which may create illuminating orderings.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] The rotation of the axes is a translation in the parallel coordinates and if the lines intersected outside the parallel axes it can be translated between them by rotations.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] The simplest example of this is rotating the axis by 180 degrees.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] Scaling is necessary because the plot is based on interpolation (linear combination) of consecutive pairs of variables.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] Therefore, the variables must be in common scale, and there are many scaling methods to be considered as part of data preparation process that can reveal more informative views.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] A smooth parallel coordinate plot is achieved with splines.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] In the smooth plot, every observation is mapped into a parametric line (or curve), which is smooth, continuous on the axes, and orthogonal to each parallel axis.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] This design emphasizes the quantization level for each data attribute.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] Inselberg (Inselberg 1997) made a full review of how to visually read out parallel coordinates relational patterns.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] When most lines between two parallel axes are somewhat parallel to each other, it suggests a positive relationship between these two dimensions.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] When lines cross in a kind of superposition of X-shapes, it's a negative relationship.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] When lines cross randomly or are parallel, it shows there is no particular relationship.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] In parallel coordinates, each axis can have at most two neighboring axes (one on the left, and one on the right).
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] For a *n*-dimensional data set, at most *n*-1 relationships can be shown at a time without altering the approach.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] In time series visualization, there exists a natural predecessor and successor; therefore in this special case, there exists a preferred arrangement.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] However, when the axes do not have a unique order, finding a good axis arrangement requires the use of experimentation and feature engineering.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] To explore more relationships, axes may be reordered or restructured.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] One approach arranges axes in 3-dimensional space (still in parallel, forming a Lattice graph), an axis can have more than two neighbors in a circle around the central attribute, and the arrangement problem can be improve by using a minimum spanning tree.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] A prototype of this visualization is available as extension to the data mining software ELKI.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] However, the visualization is harder to interpret and interact with than a linear order.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] While there are a large number of papers about parallel coordinates, there are only a few notable software publicly available to convert databases into parallel coordinates graphics.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] Notable software are ELKI, GGobi, Mondrian, and ROOT.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] Libraries include Protovis.js, D3.js provides basic examples.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] D3.Parcoords.js (a D3-based library) specifically dedicated to parallel coordinates graphic creation has also been published.
[src:bump-charts/parallel-coordinates] The Python data structure and analysis library Pandas implements parallel coordinates plotting, using the plotting library matplotlib.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] A **rank correlation coefficient** measures the degree of similarity between two rankings, and can be used to assess the significance of the relation between them.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] For example, two common nonparametric methods of significance that use rank correlation are the Mann–Whitney U test and the Wilcoxon signed-rank test.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] A rank correlation coefficient can measure that relationship, and the measure of significance of the rank correlation coefficient can show whether the measured relationship is small enough to likely be a coincidence.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] If there is only one variable, the identity of a college football program, but it is subject to two different poll rankings (say, one by coaches and one by sportswriters), then the similarity of the two different polls' rankings can be measured with a rank correlation coefficient.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] As another example, in a contingency table with *low income*, *medium income*, and *high income* in the row variable and educational level—*no high school*, *high school*, *university*—in the column variable, a rank correlation measures the relationship between income and educational level.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] An increasing rank correlation coefficient implies increasing agreement between rankings.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] Following Diaconis (1988), a ranking can be seen as a permutation of a set of objects.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] Thus we can look at observed rankings as data obtained when the sample space is (identified with) a symmetric group.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] We can then introduce a metric, making the symmetric group into a metric space.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] Different metrics will correspond to different rank correlations.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] Kendall 1970 showed that his $\tau$ (tau) and Spearman's $\rho$ (rho) are particular cases of a general correlation coefficient.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] Suppose we have a set of n objects, which are being considered in relation to two properties, represented by x and y , forming the sets of values $\{x_{i}\}_{i\leq n}$ and $\{y_{i}\}_{i\leq n}$ .
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] To any pair of individuals, say the i -th and the j -th we assign a x -score, denoted by $a_{ij}$ , and a y -score, denoted by $b_{ij}$ .
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] The only requirement for these functions is that they be anti-symmetric, so $a_{ij}=-a_{ji}$ and $b_{ij}=-b_{ji}$ .
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] where $\langle A,B\rangle _{\rm {F}}$ is the Frobenius inner product and $\|A\|_{\rm {F}}={\sqrt {\langle A,A\rangle _{\rm {F}}}}$ the Frobenius norm.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] In particular, the general correlation coefficient is the cosine of the angle between the matrices A and B .
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] The sum $\sum a_{ij}b_{ij}$ is the number of concordant pairs minus the number of discordant pairs (see Kendall tau rank correlation coefficient).
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] To simplify this expression, let $d_{i}:=r_{i}-s_{i}$ denote the difference in the ranks for each i .
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] Further, let U be a uniformly distributed discrete random variables on $\{1,2,\ldots ,n\}$ .
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] Since the ranks $r,s$ are just permutations of $1,2,\ldots ,n$ , we can view both as being random variables distributed like U .
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] where $d_{i}=r_{i}-s_{i}$ is the difference between ranks, which is exactly Spearman's rank correlation coefficient $\rho$ .
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] Gene Glass (1965) noted that the rank-biserial can be derived from Spearman's $\rho$ .
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] "One can derive a coefficient defined on *X*, the dichotomous variable, and *Y*, the ranking variable, which estimates Spearman's rho between X and Y in the same way that biserial r estimates Pearson's *r* between two normal variables" (p.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] The rank-biserial correlation had been introduced nine years before by Edward Cureton (1956) as a measure of rank correlation when the ranks are in two groups.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] Dave Kerby (2014) recommended the rank-biserial as the measure to introduce students to rank correlation, because the general logic can be explained at an introductory level.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] The rank-biserial is the correlation used with the Mann–Whitney U test, a method commonly covered in introductory college courses on statistics.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] The data for this test consists of two groups; and for each member of the groups, the outcome is ranked for the study as a whole.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] Kerby showed that this rank correlation can be expressed in terms of two concepts: the percent of data that support a stated hypothesis, and the percent of data that do not support it.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] The Kerby simple difference formula states that the rank correlation can be expressed as the difference between the proportion of favorable evidence (*f*) minus the proportion of unfavorable evidence (*u*).
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] To illustrate the computation, suppose a coach trains long-distance runners for one month using two methods.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] Group A has 5 runners, and Group B has 4 runners.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] The stated hypothesis is that method A produces faster runners.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] The race to assess the results finds that the runners from Group A do indeed run faster, with the following ranks: 1, 2, 3, 4, and 6.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] The slower runners from Group B thus have ranks of 5, 7, 8, and 9.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] The analysis is conducted on pairs, defined as a member of one group compared to a member of the other group.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] For example, the fastest runner in the study is a member of four pairs: (1,5), (1,7), (1,8), and (1,9).
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] All four of these pairs support the hypothesis, because in each pair the runner from Group A is faster than the runner from Group B.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] There are a total of 20 pairs, and 19 pairs support the hypothesis.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] The only pair that does not support the hypothesis are the two runners with ranks 5 and 6, because in this pair, the runner from Group B had the faster time.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] By the Kerby simple difference formula, 95% of the data support the hypothesis (19 of 20 pairs), and 5% do not support (1 of 20 pairs), so the rank correlation is *r* = .95 − .05 = .90.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] The maximum value for the correlation is *r* = 1, which means that 100% of the pairs favor the hypothesis.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] A correlation of *r* = 0 indicates that half the pairs favor the hypothesis and half do not; in other words, the sample groups do not differ in ranks, so there is no evidence that they come from two different populations.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] An effect size of *r* = 0 can be said to describe no relationship between group membership and the members' ranks.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] In their article “Improving statistical reporting in psychology,” Anna-Lena Schubert and her colleagues (2025) set forth guidelines for statistical reporting, drawing from established recommendations and emerging best practices.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] In Table 5 they offered an overview of effect sizes for commonly used statistical models.
[src:bump-charts/rank-correlation] In this table they cited the Kerby (2014) paper as a key resource for the application and interpretation of the rank-biserial correlation.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] In statistics, **ranking** is the data transformation in which numerical or ordinal values are replaced by their rank when the data are sorted.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] As another example, the ordinal data hot, cold, warm would be replaced by 3, 1, 2.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] In these examples, the ranks are assigned to values in ascending order, although descending ranks can also be used.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] Ranks are related to the indexed list of order statistics, which consists of the original dataset rearranged into ascending order.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] Some kinds of statistical tests employ calculations based on ranks.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] The distribution of values in decreasing order of rank is often of interest when values vary widely in scale; this is the rank-size distribution (or rank-frequency distribution), for example for city sizes or word frequencies.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] Some ranks can have non-integer values for tied data values.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] For example, when there is an even number of copies of the same data value, the fractional statistical rank of the tied data ends in ½.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] Percentile rank is another type of statistical ranking.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] Microsoft Excel provides two ranking functions, the Rank.EQ function which assigns competition ranks in the case of ties, and the Rank.AVG function which assigns fractional ranks to ties.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] Note that Rank.AVG preserves rank sums in the case of ties, whereas Rank.EQ does not.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] This makes the latter undesirable in many statistical applications.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] The functions have the order argument, which is by default is set to *descending*, i.e. the largest number will have a rank 1.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] This is generally uncommon for statistics where the ranking is usually in ascending order, where the smallest number has a rank 1.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] A rank correlation can be used to compare two rankings for the same set of objects.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] For example, Spearman's rank correlation coefficient is useful to measure the statistical dependence between the rankings of athletes in two tournaments.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] And the Kendall rank correlation coefficient is another approach.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] Alternatively, intersection/overlap-based approaches offer additional flexibility.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] One example is the "Rank–rank hypergeometric overlap" approach, which is designed to compare ranking of the genes that are at the "top" of two ordered lists of differentially expressed genes.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] A similar approach is taken by the "Rank Biased Overlap (RBO)", which also implements an adjustable probability, p, to customize the weight assigned at a desired depth of ranking.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] These approaches have the advantages of addressing disjoint sets, sets of different sizes, and top-weightedness (taking into account the absolute ranking position, which may be ignored in standard non-weighted rank correlation approaches).
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] Let $X_{1},..X_{n}$ be a set of random variables.
[src:bump-charts/ranking-statistics] If all the values are unique, the rank of variable number i is the unique solution $R_{n,i}$ to the equation $X_{i}=X_{N,(R_{n,i})}$ .
[src:bump-charts/slope-chart] A **slope chart**, also known as a **slope graph**, is a simple data visualization used to show changes between two numerical values for multiple categories.
[src:bump-charts/slope-chart] It connects paired data points across two vertical axes using straight lines, helping to highlight relative increases and decreases.
[src:bump-charts/slope-chart] The use of slope charts in visual analytics was popularized by Edward Tufte in the early 1980s.
[src:bump-charts/slope-chart] Tufte advocated for charts that maximize data-to-ink ratio, and the slope chart became an example of conveying change clearly with minimal graphic elements.
[src:bump-charts/slope-chart] A typical slope chart has two parallel vertical axes that represent two points in time or conditions.
[src:bump-charts/slope-chart] Each category’s value is plotted on both axes, and the pair is connected with a straight line.
[src:bump-charts/slope-chart] The angle of each line indicates the direction and magnitude of change.
[src:bump-charts/slope-chart] A steeper slope signifies a larger difference between the two values.
[src:bump-charts/slope-chart] If the line slopes upward from left to right, it indicates an increase; if downward, a decrease; and a horizontal line indicates no change.
[src:bump-charts/slope-chart] According to data visualization practitioners, slope charts are especially effective when there is a clear need to communicate relative position and ranking alongside the magnitude of change.
[src:bump-charts/slope-chart] Slope charts may become crowded and difficult to interpret if too many lines cross or if the number of categories is large.
[src:bump-charts/slope-chart] They are designed to compare only two data points; for longer time series, line charts or other forms are more appropriate.
[src:bump-charts/slope-chart] Slope charts are related to other comparative graphics, such as line charts, bump charts, dumbbell plots, bar charts, and dot plots, which illustrate differences or changes in ranking and numerical data.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] In mathematics, a **time series** is a sequence of data points indexed, listed, or graphed in chronological order.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Most commonly, a time series consists of observations recorded at successive equally spaced points in time.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Thus, it represents a form of discrete-time data.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] A time series may describe measurements collected over seconds, days, years, or even centuries.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Common examples include heights of ocean tides, counts of sunspots, daily temperature readings, and the closing values of stock market indices such as the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] A time series is often visualized using a run chart (a type of temporal line chart), which helps identify patterns such as trends, seasonal effects, and irregular fluctuations.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Time series data have a natural temporal ordering.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] This makes time series analysis distinct from cross-sectional studies, in which there is no natural ordering of the observations (e.g. explaining people's wages by reference to their respective education levels, where the individuals' data could be entered in any order).
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Time series analysis is also distinct from spatial data analysis where the observations typically relate to geographical locations (e.g. accounting for house prices by the location as well as the intrinsic characteristics of the houses).
[src:bump-charts/time-series] A stochastic model for a time series will generally reflect the fact that observations close together in time will be more closely related than observations further apart.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] In addition, time series models will often make use of the natural one-way ordering of time so that values for a given period will be expressed as deriving in some way from past values, rather than from future values (see time reversibility).
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Time series analysis can be applied to real-valued, continuous data, discrete numeric data, or discrete symbolic data (i.e. sequences of characters, such as letters and words in the English language).
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Methods for time series analysis may be divided into two classes: frequency-domain methods and time-domain methods.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] The former include spectral analysis and wavelet analysis; the latter include auto-correlation and cross-correlation analysis.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] In the time domain, correlation and analysis can be made in a filter-like manner using scaled correlation, thereby mitigating the need to operate in the frequency domain.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Additionally, time series analysis techniques may be divided into parametric and non-parametric methods.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] The parametric approaches assume that the underlying stationary stochastic process has a certain structure which can be described using a small number of parameters (for example, using an autoregressive or moving-average model).
[src:bump-charts/time-series] In these approaches, the task is to estimate the parameters of the model that describes the stochastic process.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] By contrast, non-parametric approaches explicitly estimate the covariance or the spectrum of the process without assuming that the process has any particular structure.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Methods of time series analysis may also be divided into linear and non-linear, and univariate and multivariate.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] A time series is one type of panel data.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Panel data is the general class, a multidimensional data set, whereas a time series data set is a one-dimensional panel (as is a cross-sectional dataset).
[src:bump-charts/time-series] A data set may exhibit characteristics of both panel data and time series data.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] One way to tell is to ask what makes one data record unique from the other records.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] If the answer is the time data field, then this is a time series data set candidate.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] If determining a unique record requires a time data field and an additional identifier which is unrelated to time (e.g. student ID, stock symbol, country code), then it is panel data candidate.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] If the differentiation lies on the non-time identifier, then the data set is a cross-sectional data set candidate.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] There are several types of motivation and data analysis available for time series which are appropriate for different purposes.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] In the context of statistics, econometrics, quantitative finance, seismology, meteorology, and geophysics the primary goal of time series analysis is forecasting.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] In the context of signal processing, control engineering and communication engineering it is used for signal detection.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Other applications are in data mining, pattern recognition and machine learning, where time series analysis can be used for clustering, classification, query by content, anomaly detection as well as forecasting.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] A simple way to examine a regular time series is manually with a line chart.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] The datagraphic shows tuberculosis deaths in the United States, along with the yearly change and the percentage change from year to year.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] The total number of deaths declined in every year until the mid-1980s, after which there were occasional increases, often proportionately - but not absolutely - quite large.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] A study of corporate data analysts found two challenges to exploratory time series analysis: discovering the shape of interesting patterns, and finding an explanation for these patterns.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Visual tools that represent time series data as heat map matrices can help overcome these challenges.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] This approach may be based on harmonic analysis and filtering of signals in the frequency domain using the Fourier transform, and spectral density estimation.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Its development was significantly accelerated during World War II by mathematician Norbert Wiener, electrical engineers Rudolf E.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Kálmán, Dennis Gabor and others for filtering signals from noise and predicting signal values at a certain point in time.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] An equivalent effect may be achieved in the time domain, as in a Kalman filter; see filtering and smoothing for more techniques.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Curve fitting is the process of constructing a curve, or mathematical function, that has the best fit to a series of data points, possibly subject to constraints.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Curve fitting can involve either interpolation, where an exact fit to the data is required, or smoothing, in which a "smooth" function is constructed that approximately fits the data.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] A related topic is regression analysis, which focuses more on questions of statistical inference such as how much uncertainty is present in a curve that is fit to data observed with random errors.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Fitted curves can be used as an aid for data visualization, to infer values of a function where no data are available, and to summarize the relationships among two or more variables.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Extrapolation refers to the use of a fitted curve beyond the range of the observed data, and is subject to a degree of uncertainty since it may reflect the method used to construct the curve as much as it reflects the observed data.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] For processes that are expected to generally grow in magnitude one of the curves in the graphic (and many others) can be fitted by estimating their parameters.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] The construction of economic time series involves the estimation of some components for some dates by interpolation between values ("benchmarks") for earlier and later dates.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Interpolation is estimation of an unknown quantity between two known quantities (historical data), or drawing conclusions about missing information from the available information ("reading between the lines").
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Interpolation is useful where the data surrounding the missing data is available and its trend, seasonality, and longer-term cycles are known.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] This is often done by using a related series known for all relevant dates.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Alternatively polynomial interpolation or spline interpolation is used where piecewise polynomial functions are fitted in time intervals such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] A different problem which is closely related to interpolation is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function (also called regression).
[src:bump-charts/time-series] The main difference between regression and interpolation is that polynomial regression gives a single polynomial that models the entire data set.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Spline interpolation, however, yield a piecewise continuous function composed of many polynomials to model the data set.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Extrapolation is the process of estimating, beyond the original observation range, the value of a variable on the basis of its relationship with another variable.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] It is similar to interpolation, which produces estimates between known observations, but extrapolation is subject to greater uncertainty and a higher risk of producing meaningless results.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] In general, a function approximation problem asks us to select a function among a well-defined class that closely matches ("approximates") a target function in a task-specific way.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Second, the target function, call it *g*, may be unknown; instead of an explicit formula, only a set of points (a time series) of the form (*x*, *g*(*x*)) is provided.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Depending on the structure of the domain and codomain of *g*, several techniques for approximating *g* may be applicable.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] For example, if *g* is an operation on the real numbers, techniques of interpolation, extrapolation, regression analysis, and curve fitting can be used.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] If the codomain (range or target set) of *g* is a finite set, one is dealing with a classification problem instead.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] A related problem of *online* time series approximation is to summarize the data in one-pass and construct an approximate representation that can support a variety of time series queries with bounds on worst-case error.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] To some extent, the different problems (regression, classification, fitness approximation) have received a unified treatment in statistical learning theory, where they are viewed as supervised learning problems.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] In statistics, prediction is a part of statistical inference.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] One particular approach to such inference is known as predictive inference, but the prediction can be undertaken within any of the several approaches to statistical inference.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Indeed, one description of statistics is that it provides a means of transferring knowledge about a sample of a population to the whole population, and to other related populations, which is not necessarily the same as prediction over time.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] When information is transferred across time, often to specific points in time, the process is known as forecasting.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Assigning time series pattern to a specific category, for example identify a word based on series of hand movements in sign language.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Splitting a time-series into a sequence of segments.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] It is often the case that a time-series can be represented as a sequence of individual segments, each with its own characteristic properties.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] For example, the audio signal from a conference call can be partitioned into pieces corresponding to the times during which each person was speaking.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] In time-series segmentation, the goal is to identify the segment boundary points in the time-series, and to characterize the dynamical properties associated with each segment.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] One can approach this problem using change-point detection, or by modeling the time-series as a more sophisticated system, such as a Markov jump linear system.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Time series data may be clustered, however special care has to be taken when considering subsequence clustering.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Subsequence time series clustering resulted in unstable (random) clusters *induced by the feature extraction* using chunking with sliding windows.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] It was found that the cluster centers (the average of the time series in a cluster - also a time series) follow an arbitrarily shifted sine pattern (regardless of the dataset, even on realizations of a random walk).
[src:bump-charts/time-series] This means that the found cluster centers are non-descriptive for the dataset because the cluster centers are always nonrepresentative sine waves.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Models for time series data can have many forms and represent different stochastic processes.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] When modeling variations in the level of a process, three broad classes of practical importance are the *autoregressive* (AR) models, the *integrated* (I) models, and the *moving-average* (MA) models.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] These three classes depend *linearly* on previous data points.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Combinations of these ideas produce autoregressive moving-average (ARMA) and autoregressive integrated moving-average (ARIMA) models.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] The autoregressive fractionally integrated moving-average (ARFIMA) model generalizes the former three.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Another important generalization is the time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) model, in which the AR coefficients are allowed to change over time, enabling the model to capture evolving or non-stationary dynamics.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Extensions of these classes to deal with vector-valued data are available under the heading of multivariate time-series models and sometimes the preceding acronyms are extended by including an initial "V" for "vector", as in VAR for vector autoregression.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] For these models, the acronyms are extended with a final "X" for "exogenous".
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) models are especially useful for analyzing non-stationary time series in which the underlying dynamics evolve over time in complex ways, not limited to classical forms of variation such as trends or seasonal patterns.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] This flexibility makes them well suited to modeling structural changes, regime shifts, or gradual evolutions in a system's behavior.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Estimation of TVAR models typically involves methods such as kernel smoothing, recursive least squares, or Kalman filtering.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Non-linear dependence of the level of a series on previous data points is of interest, partly because of the possibility of producing a chaotic time series.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] However, more importantly, empirical investigations can indicate the advantage of using predictions derived from non-linear models, over those from linear models, as for example in nonlinear autoregressive exogenous models.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Among other types of non-linear time series models, there are models to represent the changes of variance over time (heteroskedasticity).
[src:bump-charts/time-series] These models represent autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity (ARCH) and the collection comprises a wide variety of representation (GARCH, TARCH, EGARCH, FIGARCH, CGARCH, etc.).
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Here changes in variability are related to, or predicted by, recent past values of the observed series.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] This is in contrast to other possible representations of locally varying variability, where the variability might be modeled as being driven by a separate time-varying process, as in a doubly stochastic model.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Multiscale (often referred to as multiresolution) techniques decompose a given time series, attempting to illustrate time dependence at multiple scales.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] See also Markov switching multifractal (MSMF) techniques for modeling volatility evolution.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] A hidden Markov model (HMM) is a statistical Markov model in which the system being modeled is assumed to be a Markov process with unobserved (hidden) states.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] An HMM can be considered as the simplest dynamic Bayesian network.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] HMM models are widely used in speech recognition, for translating a time series of spoken words into text.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Many of these models are collected in the python package sktime.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] A number of different notations are in use for time-series analysis.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Ergodicity implies stationarity, but the converse is not necessarily the case.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Stationarity is usually classified into strict stationarity and wide-sense or second-order stationarity.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Both models and applications can be developed under each of these conditions, although the models in the latter case might be considered as only partly specified.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] In addition, time-series analysis can be applied where the series are seasonally stationary or non-stationary.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Situations where the amplitudes of frequency components change with time can be dealt with in time-frequency analysis which makes use of a time–frequency representation of a time-series or signal.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Time series can be visualized with two categories of chart: Overlapping Charts and Separated Charts.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] Jevons was the first to study times series.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] In his book he examined a number of weekly financial time series between the years 1825 to 1860 inclusive.
[src:bump-charts/time-series] These included times series of bankruptcies, currency circulation and discount rates.
